ODE VI.

TO APOLLO.

This ode may be considered the prooemium to the Secular Hymn, A.U.C. 737, although evidently written after it. As that hymn celebrates Apollo and Diana, so this ode appro- priately commences with an invocation to Apollo, whom Horace invokes (line 27) to defend the dignity of the
